We recommended that the Local Chief Executive:

1. Require La Isla Pharmacy to deliver completely all the medicines, medical supplies and  equipment contracted by the LGU;

2. Direct the Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Treasurer to deduct liquidated damages for the subsequent deliveries and claims of La Isla Pharmacy;

3. The BAC should initiate action against La Isla Pharmacy for breach of contract.

We recommended that the agency head direct the General Services Officer to document the application for disposal of unserviceable property to the COA Auditor. The application should be supported by the following forms, as appropriate pursuant to the Handbook on Property and Supply Management  System, and Section 79 of the PD No. 1445, to wit:

> Inventory and Inspection Report of Unserviceable Property  for semi-expendable materials and equipment and non-expendable supplies accompanied by any of the following, whichever is appropriate:

> Individual survey report, duly certified by the Supply Officer and head of the Agency;

> List of Missing spare parts duly certified by the Supply Officer and Head of Agency;

> Stencils of chassis and engine numbers of motor vehicles;

> Current photographs in two positions and

> Waste Materials Report for  expendable  materials, supplies and  consumables including spare parts, empty containers, and remnants from destroyed or damaged fixed assets.
